# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chloroplast
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:chloroplast/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The **ABC model of flower development** is a scientific model of the process by which flowering plants produce a pattern of gene expression in meristems that leads to the appearance of an organ oriented towards sexual reproduction, a flower.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The latter phase has been modelled using the **ABC model**, which aims to describe the biological basis of the process from the perspective of molecular and developmental genetics.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] An external stimulus is required in order to trigger the differentiation of the meristem into a flower meristem.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This stimulus will activate mitotic cell division in the apical meristem, particularly on its sides where new primordia are formed.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This same stimulus will also cause the meristem to follow a developmental pattern that will lead to the growth of floral meristems as opposed to vegetative meristems.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The main difference between these two types of meristem, apart from the obvious disparity between the objective organ, is the verticillate (or whorled) phyllotaxis, that is, the absence of stem elongation among the successive whorls or verticils of the primordium.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] These verticils follow an acropetal development, giving rise to sepals, petals, stamens and carpels.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Another difference from vegetative axillary meristems is that the floral meristem is "determined", which means that, once differentiated, its cells will no longer divide.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The identity of the organs present in the four floral verticils is a consequence of the interaction of at least three types of gene products, each with distinct functions.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] According to the ABC model, functions A and C are required in order to determine the identity of the verticils of the perianth and the reproductive verticils, respectively.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] These functions are exclusive and the absence of one of them means that the other will determine the identity of all the floral verticils.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B function allows the differentiation of petals from sepals in the secondary verticil, as well as the differentiation of the stamen from the carpel on the tertiary verticil.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Goethe's **foliar theory** was formulated in the 18th century and it suggests that the constituent parts of a flower are structurally modified leaves, which are functionally specialized for reproduction or protection.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The transition from the vegetative phase to a reproductive phase involves a dramatic change in the plant's vital cycle, perhaps the most important one, as the process must be carried out correctly in order to guarantee that the plant produces descendants.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This transition is characterised by the induction and development of the meristem of the inflorescence, which will produce a collection of flowers or one flower.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This morphogenetic change contains both endogenous and exogenous elements: For example, in order for the change to be initiated the plant must have a certain number of leaves and contain a certain level of total biomass.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Certain environmental conditions are also required such as a characteristic photoperiod.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Plant hormones play an important part in the process, with the gibberellins having a particularly important role.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are many signals that regulate the molecular biology of the process.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The following three genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana* possess both common and independent functions in floral transition: *FLOWERING LOCUS T* (*FT*), *LEAFY* (*LFY*), *SUPPRESSOR OF OVEREXPRESSION OF CONSTANS1* (*SOC1*, also called *AGAMOUS-LIKE20*).
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] *SOC1* is a MADS-box-type gene, which integrates responses to photoperiod, vernalization and gibberellins.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The meristem can be defined as the tissue or group of plant tissues that contain undifferentiated stem cells, which are capable of producing any type of cell tissue.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Their maintenance and development, both in the vegetative meristem or the meristem of the inflorescence is controlled by genetic cell fate determination mechanisms.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that a number of genes will directly regulate, for example, the maintenance of the stem cell's characteristics (gene *WUSCHEL* or *WUS*), and others will act via negative feedback mechanisms in order to inhibit a characteristic (gene *CLAVATA* or *CLV*).
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this way both mechanisms give rise to a feedback loop, which along with other elements lend a great deal of robustness to the system.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Along with the *WUS* gene the *SHOOTMERISTEMLESS* (*STM*) gene also represses the differentiation of the meristematic dome.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This gene acts by inhibiting the possible differentiation of the stem cells but still allows cell division in the daughter cells, which, had they been allowed to differentiate, would have given rise to distinct organs.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] A flower's anatomy, as defined by the presence of a series of organs (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels) positioned according to a given pattern, facilitate sexual reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model of flower development was first formulated by George Haughn and Chris Somerville in 1988.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was first used as a model to describe the collection of genetic mechanisms that establish floral organ identity in the Rosids, as exemplified by *Arabidopsis thaliana*, and the Asterids, as demonstrated by *Antirrhinum majus*.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both species have four verticils (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels), which are defined by the differential expression of a number of homeotic genes present in each verticil.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that the sepals are solely characterized by the expression of A genes, while the petals are characterized by the co-expression of A and B genes.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B and C genes establish the identity of the stamens and the carpels only require C genes to be active.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Type A and C genes are reciprocally antagonistic.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The fact that these homeotic genes determine an organ's identity becomes evident when a gene that represents a particular function, for example the A gene, is not expressed.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* this loss results in a flower which is composed of one verticil of carpels, another containing stamens and another of carpels.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This method for studying gene function uses reverse genetics techniques to produce transgenic plants that contain a mechanism for gene silencing through RNA interference.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In other studies, using forward genetics techniques such as genetic mapping, it is the analysis of the phenotypes of flowers with structural anomalies that leads to the cloning of the gene of interest.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The flowers may possess a non-functional or over expressed allele for the gene being studied.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The existence of two supplementary functions, D and E, have also been proposed in addition to the A, B and C functions already discussed.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function D specifies the identity of the ovule, as a separate reproductive function from the development of the carpels, which occurs after their determination.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function E relates to a physiological requirement that is a characteristic of all floral verticils, although, it was initially described as necessary for the development of the three innermost verticils (Function E *sensu stricto*).
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, its broader definition (*sensu lato*) suggests that it is required in the four verticils.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The gene products of genes with D and E functions are also MADS-box genes.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The methodology for studying flower development involves two steps.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Firstly, the identification of the exact genes required for determining the identity of the floral meristem.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* these include APETALA1 (*AP1*) and LEAFY (*LFY*).
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Secondly, genetic analysis is carried out on the aberrant phenotypes for the relative characteristics of the flowers, which allows the characterization of the homeotic genes implicated in the process.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are a great many mutations that affect floral morphology, although the analysis of these mutants is a recent development.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Supporting evidence for the existence of these mutations comes from the fact that a large number affect the identity of floral organs.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] For example, some organs develop in a location where others should develop.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is called homeotic mutation, which is analogous to HOX gene mutations found in *Drosophila*.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* and *Antirrhinum*, the two taxa on which models are based, these mutations always affect adjacent verticils.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Cloning studies have been carried out on DNA in the genes associated with the affected homeotic functions in the mutants discussed above.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] These studies used serial analysis of gene expression throughout floral development to show patterns of tissue expression, which, in general, correspond with the predictions of the ABC model.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The nature of these genes corresponds to that of transcription factors, which, as expected, have analogous structures to a group of factors contained in yeasts and animal cells.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This group is called MADS, which is an acronym for the different factors contained in the group.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] These MADS factors have been detected in all the vegetable species studied, although the involvement of other elements involved in the regulation of gene expression cannot be discounted.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, function A is mainly represented by two genes *APETALA1* (*AP1)* and *APETALA2* (*AP2*) *AP1* is a MADS-box type gene, while *AP2* belongs to the family of genes that contains AP2, which it gives its name to and which consists of transcription factors that are only found in plants.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] AP2 has also been shown to complex with the co-repressor TOPLESS (TPL) in developing floral buds to repress the C-class gene *AGAMOUS* (*AG*).
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] *AP2* not only functions in the first two verticils, but also in the remaining two, in developing ovules and even in leaves.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] It is also likely that post-transcriptional regulation exists, which controls its A function, or even that it has other purposes in the determination of organ identity independent of that mentioned here.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Antirrhinum*, the orthologous gene to *AP1* is *SQUAMOSA* (*SQUA*), which also has a particular impact on the floral meristem.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs for *AP2* are *LIPLESS1* (*LIP1*) and *LIPLESS2* (*LIP2*), which have a redundant function and are of special interest in the development of sepals, petals and ovules.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] A total of three genes have been isolated from *Petunia hybrida* that are similar to *AP2*: *P. hybrida APETALA2A* (*PhAP2A*), *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] *PhAP2A* is, to a large degree, homologous with the *AP2* gene of *Arabidopsis*, both in its sequence and in its expression pattern, which suggests that the two genes are orthologs.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The proteins *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*, on the other hand, are slightly different, even though they belong to the family of transcription factors that are similar to *AP2*.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition they are expressed in different ways, although they are very similar in comparison with *PhAP2A*.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In fact, the mutants for these genes do not show the usual phenotype, that of the null alleles of A genes.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* the type-B function mainly arises from two genes, *APETALA3* (*AP3*) and *PISTILLATA* (*PI*), both of which are MADS-box genes.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] A mutation of either of these genes causes the homeotic conversion of petals into sepals and of stamens into carpels.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This also occurs in its orthologs in *A. majus*, which are DEFICIENS (*DEF*) and *GLOBOSA* (*GLO*) respectively.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] For both species the active form of binding with DNA is that derived from the heterodimer: AP3 and PI, or DEF and GLO, dimerize.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is the form in which they are able to function.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *GLO*/*PI* lines that have been duplicated in *Petunia* contain *P. hybrida GLOBOSA1* (*PhGLO1*, also called *FBP1*) and also *PhGLO2* (also called *PMADS2* or *FBP3*).
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] For the functional elements equivalent to *AP3*/*DEF* in *Petunia* there is both a gene that possesses a relatively similar sequence, called *PhDEF* and there is also an atypical B function gene called PhTM6.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic studies have placed the first three within the «euAP3» lineage, while PhTM6 belongs to that of «paleoAP3».
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] As discussed above, the floral organs of eudicotyledonous angiosperms are arranged in 4 different verticils, containing the sepals, petals, stamen and carpels.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model states that the identity of these organs is determined by the homeotic genes A, A+B, B+C and C, respectively.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In contrast with the sepal and petal verticils of the eudicots, the perigone of many plants of the family Liliaceae have two nearly identical external petaloid verticils (the tepals).
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In order to explain the floral morphology of the Liliaceae, van Tunen *et al.* proposed a modified ABC model in 1993.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This model suggests that class B genes are not only expressed in verticils 2 and 3, but also in 1.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] It therefore follows that the organs of verticils 1 and 2 express class A and B genes and this is how they have a petaloid structure.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] This theoretical model has been experimentally proven through the cloning and characterization of homologs of the *Antirrhinum* genes *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* in a Liliaceae, the tulip *Tulipa gesneriana*.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are expressed in verticils 1,2 and 3.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* have also been isolated and characterized in *Agapanthus praecox* ssp.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] *orientalis* (Agapanthaceae), which is phylogenetically distant from the model organisms.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this study the genes were called *ApGLO* and *ApDEF*, respectively.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both contain open reading frames that code for proteins with 210 to 214 amino acids.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic analysis of these sequences indicated that they belong to B gene family of the monocotyledons.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In situ hybridization studies revealed that both sequences are expressed in verticil 1 as well as in 2 and 3.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] When taken together, these observations show that the floral development mechanism of *Agapanthus* also follows the modified ABC model.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, the C function is derived from one MADS-box type gene called *AGAMOUS* (*AG*), which intervenes both in the establishment of stamen and carpel identity as well as in the determination of the floral meristem.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Therefore, the *AG* mutants are devoid of androecium and gynoecium and they have petals and sepals in their place.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition, the growth in the centre of the flower is undifferentiated, therefore the petals and sepals grow in repetitive verticils.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *PLENA* (*PLE*) gene is present in *A. majus*, in place of the *AG* gene, although it is not an ortholog.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, the *FARINELLI* (*FAR*) gene is an ortholog, which is specific to the development of the anthers and the maturation of pollen.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Petunia*, *Antirrhinum* and in maize the C function is controlled by a number of genes that act in the same manner.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The genes that are closer homologs of *AG* in *Petunia* are *pMADS3* and *floral-binding protein 6* (*FBP6*).
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The D function genes were discovered in 1995.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are MADS-box proteins and they have a function that is distinct from those previously described, although they have a certain homology with C function genes.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are called *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN7* (*FBP7*) and *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN1L* (*FBP1l*).
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was found that, in *Petunia*, they are involved in the development of the ovule.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] Equivalent genes were later found in *Arabidopsis*, where they are also involved in controlling the development of carpels and the ovule and even with structures related to seed dispersal.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The appearance of interesting phenotypes in RNA interference studies in *Petunia* and tomato led, in 1994, to the definition of a new type of function in the floral development model.
[src:chloroplast/abc-model-of-flower-development] The E function was initially thought to be only involved in the development of the three innermost verticils, however, subsequent work found that its expression was required in all the floral verticils.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:chloroplast/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] In the 1940s, Torsten Hemberg, while working at the University of Stockholm, found evidence that a positive correlation exists between the rest period and the occurrence of an acidic ether soluble growth inhibitor in potato tubers.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] In 1963, abscisic acid was first identified and characterized as a plant hormone by Frederick T.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] They were studying compounds that cause abscission (shedding) of cotton fruits (bolls).
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Two compounds were isolated and called abscisin I and abscisin II.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Abscisin II is presently called abscisic acid (ABA).
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] ABA was originally believed to be involved in abscission, which is how it received its name.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] This is now known to be the case only in a small number of plants.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] ABA-mediated signaling also plays an important part in plant responses to environmental stress and plant pathogens.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] The plant genes for ABA biosynthesis and sequence of the pathway have been elucidated.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] ABA is also produced by some plant pathogenic fungi via a biosynthetic route different from ABA biosynthesis in plants.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] In preparation for winter, ABA is produced in terminal buds.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] This slows plant growth and directs leaf primordia to develop scales to protect the dormant buds during the cold season.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] ABA also inhibits the division of cells in the vascular cambium, adjusting to cold conditions in the winter by suspending primary and secondary growth.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Abscisic acid is also produced in the roots in response to decreased soil water potential (which is associated with dry soil) and other situations in which the plant may be under stress.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] ABA then translocates to the leaves, where it rapidly alters the osmotic potential of stomatal guard cells, causing them to shrink and stomata to close.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] The ABA-induced stomatal closure reduces transpiration (evaporation of water out of the stomata), thus preventing further water loss from the leaves in times of low water availability.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] A close linear correlation was found between the ABA content of the leaves and their conductance (stomatal resistance) on a leaf area basis.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Seed germination is inhibited by ABA in antagonism with gibberellin.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] ABA also prevents loss of seed dormancy.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Several ABA-mutant *Arabidopsis thaliana* plants have been identified and are available from the Nottingham Arabidopsis Stock Centre - both those deficient in ABA production and those with altered sensitivity to its action.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Plants that are hypersensitive or insensitive to ABA show phenotypes in seed dormancy, germination, stomatal regulation, and some mutants show stunted growth and brown/yellow leaves.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] These mutants reflect the importance of ABA in seed germination and early embryo development.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Pyrabactin (a pyridyl containing ABA activator) is a naphthalene sulfonamide hypocotyl cell expansion inhibitor, which is an agonist of the seed ABA signaling pathway.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] It is the first agonist of the ABA pathway that is not structurally related to ABA.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Abamine has been designed, synthesized, developed and then patented as the first specific ABA biosynthesis inhibitor, which makes it possible to regulate endogenous levels of ABA.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] ABA can be catabolized to phaseic acid via CYP707A (a group of P450 enzymes) or inactivated by glucose conjugation (ABA-glucose ester) via the enzyme uridine diphosphate-glucosyltransferase (UDP-glucosyltransferase).
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Catabolism via the CYP707As is very important for ABA homeostasis, and mutants in those genes generally accumulate higher levels of ABA than lines overexpressing ABA biosynthetic genes.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] In soil bacteria, an alternative catabolic pathway leading to dehydrovomifoliol via the enzyme vomifoliol dehydrogenase has been reported.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] In the absence of ABA, the phosphatase ABA-INSENSITIVE1 (ABI1) inhibits the action of SNF1-related protein kinases (subfamily 2) (SnRK2s).
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] ABA is perceived by the PYRABACTIN RESISTANCE 1 (PYR1) and PYR1-like membrane proteins.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] On ABA binding, PYR1 binds to and inhibits ABI1.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] When SnRK2s are released from inhibition, they activate several transcription factors from the ABA RESPONSIVE ELEMENT-BINDING FACTOR (ABF) family.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] ABFs then go on to cause changes in the expression of a large number of genes.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Around 10% of plant genes are thought to be regulated by ABA.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Like plants, some fungal species (for example *Cercospora rosicola*, *Botrytis cinerea* and *Magnaporthe oryzae*) have an endogenous biosynthesis pathway for ABA.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] In fungi, it seems to be the MVA biosynthetic pathway that is predominant (rather than the MEP pathway that is responsible for ABA biosynthesis in plants).
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] One role of ABA produced by these pathogens seems to be to suppress the plant immune responses.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] ABA has also been found to be present in metazoans, from sponges up to mammals including humans.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Currently, its biosynthesis and biological role in animals is poorly known.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] ABA elicits potent anti-inflammatory and anti-diabetic effects in mouse models of diabetes/obesity, inflammatory bowel disease, atherosclerosis and influenza infection.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Many biological effects in animals have been studied using ABA as a nutraceutical or pharmacognostic drug, but ABA is also generated endogenously by some cells (like macrophages) when stimulated.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] There are also conflicting conclusions from different studies, where some claim that ABA is essential for pro-inflammatory responses whereas other show anti-inflammatory effects.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Like with many natural substances with medical properties, ABA has become popular also in naturopathy.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] While ABA clearly has beneficial biological activities and many naturopathic remedies will contain high levels of ABA (such as wheatgrass juice, fruits and vegetables), some of the health claims made may be exaggerated or overly optimistic.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] In mammalian cells ABA targets a protein known as lanthionine synthetase C-like 2 (LANCL2), triggering an alternative mechanism of activation of peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPAR gamma).
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] LANCL2 is conserved in plants and was originally suggested to be an ABA receptor also in plants, which was later challenged.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Several methods can help to quantify the concentration of abscisic acid in a variety of plant tissue.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] The quantitative methods used are based on HPLC and ELISA.
[src:chloroplast/abscisic-acid] Two independent FRET probes can measure intracellular ABA concentrations in real time in vivo.
[src:chloroplast/accessory-pigments] The result is that, in vivo, a composite absorption spectrum of all these pigments is broadened and flattened such that a wider range of visible and infrared radiation is absorbed by plants and algae.
[src:chloroplast/accessory-pigments] Most photosynthetic organisms do not absorb green light well, thus most remaining light under leaf canopies in forests or under water with abundant plankton is green, a spectral effect called the "green window".
[src:chloroplast/accessory-pigments] Organisms such as some cyanobacteria and red algae contain accessory phycobiliproteins that absorb green light reaching these habitats.
[src:chloroplast/accessory-pigments] In aquatic ecosystems, it is likely that the absorption spectrum of water, along with gilvin and tripton (dissolved and particulate organic matter, respectively), determines phototrophic niche differentiation.
[src:chloroplast/accessory-pigments] The six shoulders in the light absorption of water between wavelengths 400 and 1100 nm correspond to troughs in the collective absorption of at least twenty diverse species of phototrophic bacteria.
[src:chloroplast/accessory-pigments] Another effect is due to the overall trend for water to absorb low frequencies, while gilvin and tripton absorb higher ones.
[src:chloroplast/accessory-pigments] This is why open ocean appears blue and supports yellow species such as *Prochlorococcus*, which contains divinyl-chlorophyll *a* and *b*.
[src:chloroplast/accessory-pigments] *Synechococcus*, colored red with phycoerythrin, is adapted to coastal bodies, while phycocyanin allows Cyanobacteria to thrive in darker inland waters.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] ClpS is an N-recognin in the N-end rule pathway.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] ClpS interacts with protein substrates that have a bulky hydrophobic residue (leucine, phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan) at the N-terminus.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] The protein substrate is then degraded by the ClpAP protease.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] In molecular biology, the **ATP-dependent Clp protease adaptor protein ClpS** is a bacterial protein.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] In the bacterial cytosol, ATP-dependent protein degradation is performed by several different chaperone-protease pairs, including ClpAP.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] ClpS directly influences the ClpAP machine by binding to the N-terminal domain of the chaperone ClpA.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] The degradation of ClpAP substrates, both SsrA-tagged proteins and ClpA itself, is specifically inhibited by ClpS.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] ClpS modifies ClpA substrate specificity, potentially redirecting degradation by ClpAP toward aggregated proteins.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] ClpS is a small alpha/beta protein that consists of three alpha-helices connected to three antiparallel beta-strands.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] The protein has a globular shape, with a curved layer of three antiparallel alpha-helices over a twisted antiparallel beta-sheet.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] Dimerization of ClpS may occur through its N-terminal domain.
[src:chloroplast/atp-dependent-clp-protease-adaptor-protein-clps] This short extended N-terminal region in ClpS is followed by the central seven-residue beta-strand, which is flanked by two other beta-strands in a small beta-sheet.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] ATP synthase lies across a cellular membrane and forms an aperture that protons can cross from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration, imparting energy for the synthesis of ATP.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] This electrochemical gradient is generated by the electron transport chain and allows cells to store energy in ATP for later use.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] In prokaryotic cells ATP synthase lies across the plasma membrane, while in eukaryotic cells it lies across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Organisms capable of photosynthesis also have ATP synthase across the thylakoid membrane, which in plants is located in the chloroplast and in cyanobacteria is located in the cytoplasm.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] ATP synthase is present in all organisms studied.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Eukaryotic ATP synthases are F-ATPases (which usually work as ATP synthases instead of ATPases in cellular environments) and running "in reverse" for an ATPase (ATPases catalyze the decomposition of ATP into ADP and a free phosphate ion).
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] This article deals mainly with this type.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] An F-ATPase consists of two main subunits, FO and F1, which has a rotational motor mechanism allowing for ATP production.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The F1 fraction derives its name from the term "Fraction 1" and FO (written as a subscript letter "o", not "zero") derives its name from being the binding fraction for oligomycin, a type of naturally derived antibiotic that is able to inhibit the FO unit of ATP synthase.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] These functional regions consist of different protein subunits — refer to tables.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] This enzyme is used in synthesis of ATP through aerobic respiration.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Located within the thylakoid membrane and the inner mitochondrial membrane, ATP synthase consists of two regions FO and F1.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] FO causes rotation of F1 and is made of c-ring and subunits a, two b, F6.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] F1 has a water-soluble part that can hydrolyze ATP.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] FO on the other hand has mainly hydrophobic regions.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] FO F1 creates a pathway for protons movement across the membrane.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The F1 portion of ATP synthase is hydrophilic and responsible for hydrolyzing ATP.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The F1 unit protrudes into the cytoplasm (matrix and stroma in mitochondria and chloroplasts respectively).
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Subunits α and β make a hexamer with 6 binding sites.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Three of them are catalytically inactive and they bind ADP.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Three other subunits catalyze the ATP synthesis.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The other F1 subunits γ, δ, and ε are a part of a rotational motor mechanism (rotor/axle).
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The γ subunit allows β to go through conformational changes (i.e., closed, half open, and open states) that allow for ATP to be bound and released once synthesized.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The F1 particle is large and can be seen in the transmission electron microscope by negative staining.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] These are particles of 9 nm diameter that pepper the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] FO is a water insoluble protein with eight subunits and a transmembrane ring.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The FO region of ATP synthase is a proton pore that is embedded in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] It consists of three main subunits, a, b, and c.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Six c subunits make up the rotor ring, and subunit b makes up a stalk connecting to F1 OSCP that prevents the αβ hexamer from rotating.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Humans have six additional subunits, d, e, f, g, F6, and 8 (or A6L).
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] This part of the enzyme is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and couples proton translocation to the rotation that causes ATP synthesis in the F1 region.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] In eukaryotes, mitochondrial FO forms membrane-bending dimers.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] These dimers self-arrange into long rows at the end of the cristae, possibly the first step of cristae formation.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] An atomic model for the dimeric yeast FO region was determined by cryo-EM at an overall resolution of 3.6 Å.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] In the 1960s through the 1970s, Paul Boyer, a UCLA Professor, developed the binding change, or flip-flop, mechanism theory, which postulated that ATP synthesis is dependent on a conformational change in ATP synthase generated by rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Walker, then at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge, crystallized the F1 catalytic-domain of ATP synthase.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The structure, at the time the largest asymmetric protein structure known, indicated that Boyer's rotary-catalysis model was, in essence, correct.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] For elucidating this, Boyer and Walker shared half of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The crystal structure of the F1 showed alternating alpha and beta subunits (3 of each), arranged like segments of an orange around a rotating asymmetrical gamma subunit.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] A portion of the FO (the ring of c-subunits) rotates as the protons pass through the membrane.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The c-ring is tightly attached to the asymmetric central stalk (consisting primarily of the gamma subunit), causing it to rotate within the alpha3beta3 of F1 causing the 3 catalytic nucleotide binding sites to go through a series of conformational changes that lead to ATP synthesis.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The major F1 subunits are prevented from rotating in sympathy with the central stalk rotor by a peripheral stalk that joins the alpha3beta3 to the non-rotating portion of FO.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The structure of the intact ATP synthase is currently known at low-resolution from electron cryo-microscopy (cryo-EM) studies of the complex.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The cryo-EM model of ATP synthase suggests that the peripheral stalk is a flexible structure that wraps around the complex as it joins F1 to FO.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Under the right conditions, the enzyme reaction can also be carried out in reverse, with ATP hydrolysis driving proton pumping across the membrane.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The binding change mechanism involves the active site of a β subunit's cycling between three states.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] In the "loose" state, ADP and phosphate enter the active site; in the adjacent diagram, this is shown in pink.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The enzyme then undergoes a change in shape and forces these molecules together, with the active site in the resulting "tight" state (shown in red) binding the newly produced ATP molecule with very high affinity.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Finally, the active site cycles back to the open state (orange), releasing ATP and binding more ADP and phosphate, ready for the next cycle of ATP production.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Like other enzymes, the activity of F1FO ATP synthase is reversible.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Large-enough quantities of ATP cause it to create a transmembrane proton gradient, this is used by fermenting bacteria that do not have an electron transport chain, but rather hydrolyze ATP to make a proton gradient, which they use to drive flagella and the transport of nutrients into the cell.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] In respiring bacteria under physiological conditions, ATP synthase, in general, runs in the opposite direction, creating ATP while using the proton motive force created by the electron transport chain as a source of energy.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The overall process of creating energy in this fashion is termed oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The same process takes place in the mitochondria, where ATP synthase is located in the inner mitochondrial membrane and the F1-part projects into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] By pumping proton cations into the matrix, the ATP-synthase converts ADP into ATP.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The evolution of ATP synthase is thought to have been modular whereby two functionally independent subunits became associated and gained new functionality.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] This association appears to have occurred early in evolutionary history, because essentially the same structure and activity of ATP synthase enzymes are present in all kingdoms of life.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The F-ATP synthase displays high functional and mechanistic similarity to the V-ATPase.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] However, whereas the F-ATP synthase generates ATP by utilising a proton gradient, the V-ATPase generates a proton gradient at the expense of ATP, generating pH values of as low as 1.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The F1 region also shows significant similarity to hexameric DNA helicases (especially the Rho factor), and the entire enzyme region shows some similarity to H+ -powered T3SS or flagellar motor complexes.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The α3β3 hexamer of the F1 region shows significant structural similarity to hexameric DNA helicases; both form a ring with 3-fold rotational symmetry with a central pore.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The H+ motor of the FO particle shows great functional similarity to the H+ motors that drive flagella.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Both feature a ring of many small alpha-helical proteins that rotate relative to nearby stationary proteins, using a H+ potential gradient as an energy source.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] This link is tenuous, however, as the overall structure of flagellar motors is far more complex than that of the FO particle and the ring with about 30 rotating proteins is far larger than the 10, 11, or 14 helical proteins in the FO complex.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] More recent structural data do however show that the ring and the stalk are structurally similar to the F1 particle.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The modular evolution theory for the origin of ATP synthase suggests that two subunits with independent function, a DNA helicase with ATPase activity and a H+ motor, were able to bind, and the rotation of the motor drove the ATPase activity of the helicase in reverse.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] This complex then evolved greater efficiency and eventually developed into today's intricate ATP synthases.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Alternatively, the DNA helicase/H+ motor complex may have had H+ pump activity with the ATPase activity of the helicase driving the H+ motor in reverse.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] This may have evolved to carry out the reverse reaction and act as an ATP synthase.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] A variety of natural and synthetic inhibitors of ATP synthase have been discovered.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] These have been used to probe the structure and mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] There are several classes of ATP synthase inhibitors, including peptide inhibitors, polyphenolic phytochemicals, polyketides, organotin compounds, polyenic α-pyrone derivatives, cationic inhibitors, substrate analogs, amino acid modifiers, and other miscellaneous chemicals.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Some of the most commonly used ATP synthase inhibitors are oligomycin and DCCD.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Bacterial F-ATPases can occasionally operate in reverse, turning them into an ATPase.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Some bacteria have no F-ATPase, using an A/V-type ATPase bidirectionally.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Yeast ATP synthase is one of the best-studied eukaryotic ATP synthases; and five F1, eight FO subunits, and seven associated proteins have been identified.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Most of these proteins have homologues in other eukaryotes.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] In plants, ATP synthase is also present in chloroplasts (CF1FO-ATP synthase).
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The enzyme is integrated into thylakoid membrane; the CF1-part sticks into stroma, where dark reactions of photosynthesis (also called the light-independent reactions or the Calvin cycle) and ATP synthesis take place.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The overall structure and the catalytic mechanism of the chloroplast ATP synthase are almost the same as those of the bacterial enzyme.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] However, in chloroplasts, the proton motive force is generated not by respiratory electron transport chain but by primary photosynthetic proteins.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The synthase has a 40-aa insert in the gamma-subunit to inhibit wasteful activity when dark.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The ATP synthase isolated from bovine (*Bos taurus*) heart mitochondria is, in terms of biochemistry and structure, the best-characterized ATP synthase.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Beef heart is used as a source for the enzyme because of the high concentration of mitochondria in cardiac muscle.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Their genes have close homology to human ATP synthases.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Eukaryotes belonging to some divergent lineages have very special organizations of the ATP synthase.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] A euglenozoa ATP synthase forms a dimer with a boomerang-shaped F1 head like other mitochondrial ATP synthases, but the FO subcomplex has many unique subunits.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] The inhibitory IF1 also binds differently, in a way shared with trypanosomatida.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Apicomplexans, such as *Plasmodium*, utilise a hexameric ATP synthase organisation existing as a trimer of ATP synthase dimers.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] These hexameric assemblies arrange into pentagonal pyramids, which induce a unique bulbous cristae membrane morphology.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] This organisation is underpinned by both apicomplexan-specific subunits and cardiolipins.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Archaea do not generally have an F-ATPase.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Instead, they synthesize ATP using the A-ATPase/synthase, a rotary machine structurally similar to the V-ATPase but mainly functioning as an ATP synthase.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] Like the bacteria F-ATPase, it is believed to also function as an ATPase.
[src:chloroplast/atp-synthase] F-ATPase gene linkage and gene order are widely conserved across ancient prokaryote lineages, implying that this system already existed at a date before the last universal common ancestor, the LUCA.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] A **chloroplast** (/ˈklɔːrəˌplæst, -plɑːst/ *KLOR-ə-plast, -⁠plahst*) is a type of organelle known as a plastid that conducts photosynthesis mostly in plant and algal cells.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplasts have a high concentration of chlorophyll pigments which capture the energy from sunlight, convert it to chemical energy and decomposing water to release oxygen.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The chemical energy created is then used to make sugar and other organic molecules from carbon dioxide in the Calvin cycle.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplasts carry out a number of other functions, including fatty acid synthesis, amino acid synthesis, and immune response in plants.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The number of chloroplasts per cell varies from one, in some unicellular algae, up to 100 in plants like *Arabidopsis* and wheat.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplasts are highly dynamic - they circulate and are moved around within cells.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Their behavior is strongly influenced by environmental factors, such as light color and intensity.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplasts cannot be made anew by the plant cell and must be inherited by each daughter cell during cell division, which is thought to be inherited from their ancestor—an ancient photosynthetic cyanobacterium that was engulfed by an early eukaryotic cell.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Because of their endosymbiotic origins, chloroplasts, like mitochondria, contain their own DNA separate from the cell nucleus.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] With one exception (the amoeboid *Paulinella chromatophora*), all chloroplasts can be traced back to a single endosymbiotic event.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Despite this, chloroplasts can be found in extremely diverse organisms that are not directly related to each other—a consequence of many secondary and even tertiary endosymbiotic events.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The first definitive description of a chloroplast (*Chlorophyllkörnen*, "grain of chlorophyll") was given by Hugo von Mohl in 1837 as discrete bodies within the green plant cell.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In 1883, Andreas Franz Wilhelm Schimper named these bodies as "chloroplastids" (*Chloroplastida*).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In 1884, Eduard Strasburger adopted the term "chloroplasts" (*Chloroplasten*).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The word *chloroplast* is derived from the Greek words *chloros* (χλωρός), which means green, and *plastes* (πλάστης), which means "the one who forms".
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplasts are one of many types of organelles in photosynthetic eukaryotic cells.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] They evolved from cyanobacteria through a process called organellogenesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Cyanobacteria are a diverse phylum of gram-negative bacteria capable of carrying out oxygenic photosynthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Like chloroplasts, they have thylakoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The thylakoid membranes contain photosynthetic pigments, including chlorophyll *a*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] This origin of chloroplasts was first suggested by the Russian biologist Konstantin Mereschkowski in 1905 after Andreas Franz Wilhelm Schimper observed in 1883 that chloroplasts closely resemble cyanobacteria.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplasts are only found in plants, algae, and some species of the amoeboid *Paulinella*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Mitochondria are thought to have come from a similar endosymbiosis event, where an aerobic prokaryote was engulfed.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Approximately two billion years ago, a free-living cyanobacterium entered an early eukaryotic cell, either as food or as an internal parasite, but managed to escape the phagocytic vacuole it was contained in and persist inside the cell.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] This event is called *endosymbiosis*, or "cell living inside another cell with a mutual benefit for both".
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The external cell is commonly referred to as the *host* while the internal cell is called the *endosymbiont*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The engulfed cyanobacteria provided an advantage to the host by providing sugar from photosynthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Over time, the cyanobacterium was assimilated, and many of its genes were lost or transferred to the nucleus of the host.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Some of the cyanobacterial proteins were then synthesized by the host cell and imported back into the chloroplast (formerly the cyanobacterium), allowing the host to control the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplasts which can be traced back directly to a cyanobacterial ancestor (i.e. without a subsequent endosymbiotic event) are known as ***primary plastids*** ("plastid" in this context means almost the same thing as chloroplast).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplasts that can be traced back to another photosynthetic eukaryotic endosymbiont are called ***secondary plastids*** or ***tertiary plastids*** (discussed below).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Whether primary chloroplasts came from a single endosymbiotic event or multiple independent engulfments across various eukaryotic lineages was long debated.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] It is now generally held that with one exception (the amoeboid *Paulinella chromatophora*), chloroplasts arose from a single endosymbiotic event around two billion years ago and these chloroplasts all share a single ancestor.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] It has been proposed that the closest living relative of the ancestral engulfed cyanobacterium is *Gloeomargarita lithophora.* Separately, somewhere about 90–140 million years ago, this process happened again in the amoeboid *Paulinella* with a cyanobacterium in the genus *Prochlorococcus*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] This independently evolved chloroplast is often called a *chromatophore* instead of a chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplasts are believed to have arisen after mitochondria, since all eukaryotes contain mitochondria, but not all have chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] This is called *serial endosymbiosis*—where an early eukaryote engulfed the mitochondrion ancestor, and then descendants of it then engulfed the chloroplast ancestor, creating a cell with both chloroplasts and mitochondria.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] being engulfed by another eukaryote, forming a chloroplast with three or four membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Many other organisms obtained chloroplasts from the primary chloroplast lineages through secondary endosymbiosis—engulfing a red or green alga with a primary chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] These chloroplasts are known as **secondary plastids**.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] As a result of the secondary endosymbiotic event, secondary chloroplasts have additional membranes outside of the original two in primary chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In secondary plastids, typically only the chloroplast, and sometimes its cell membrane and nucleus remain, forming a chloroplast with three or four membranes—the two cyanobacterial membranes, sometimes the eaten alga's cell membrane, and the phagosomal vacuole from the host's cell membrane.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The genes in the phagocytosed eukaryotes nucleus are often transferred to the secondary host's nucleus.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Cryptomonas and chlorarachniophytes retain the phagocytosed eukaryotes nucleus, an object called a nucleomorph, located between the second and third membranes of the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] All secondary chloroplasts come from green and red algae.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] No secondary chloroplasts from glaucophytes have been observed, probably because glaucophytes are relatively rare in nature, making them less likely to have been taken up by another eukaryote.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Still other organisms, including the dinoflagellates *Karlodinium* and *Karenia,* obtained chloroplasts by engulfing an organism with a secondary plastid.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] All primary chloroplasts belong to one of four chloroplast lineages—the glaucophyte chloroplast lineage, the rhodophyte ("red") chloroplast lineage, the chloroplastida ("green") chloroplast lineage, and the amoeboid *Paulinella chromatophora* lineage.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The glaucophyte, rhodophyte, and chloroplastidian lineages are all descended from the same ancestral endosymbiotic event and are all within the group Archaeplastida.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] with two chloroplasts in the process of dividing.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The glaucophyte chloroplast group is the smallest of the three primary chloroplast lineages as there are only 25 described glaucophyte species.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Glaucophytes diverged first before the red and green chloroplast lineages diverged.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Because of this, they are sometimes considered intermediates between cyanobacteria and the red and green chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] This early divergence is supported by both phylogenetic studies and physical features present in glaucophyte chloroplasts and cyanobacteria, but not the red and green chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] First, glaucophyte chloroplasts have a peptidoglycan wall, a type of cell wall otherwise only in bacteria (including cyanobacteria).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Second, glaucophyte chloroplasts contain concentric unstacked thylakoids which surround a carboxysome – an icosahedral structure that contains the enzyme RuBisCO responsible for carbon fixation.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Third, starch created by the chloroplast is collected outside the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Additionally, like cyanobacteria, both glaucophyte and rhodophyte thylakoids are studded with light collecting structures called phycobilisomes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The rhodophyte, or red algae, group is a large and diverse lineage.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Rhodophyte chloroplasts are also called *rhodoplasts*, literally "red chloroplasts".
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Rhodoplasts have a double membrane with an intermembrane space and phycobilin pigments organized into phycobilisomes on the thylakoid membranes, preventing their thylakoids from stacking.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Rhodoplasts have chlorophyll *a* and phycobilins for photosynthetic pigments; the phycobilin phycoerythrin is responsible for giving many red algae their distinctive red color.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] However, since they also contain the blue-green chlorophyll *a* and other pigments, many are reddish to purple from the combination.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The red phycoerythrin pigment is an adaptation to help red algae catch more sunlight in deep water—as such, some red algae that live in shallow water have less phycoerythrin in their rhodoplasts, and can appear more greenish.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Rhodoplasts synthesize a form of starch called floridean starch, which collects into granules outside the rhodoplast, in the cytoplasm of the red alga.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The chloroplastida group is another large, highly diverse lineage that includes both green algae and land plants.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] This group is also called Viridiplantae, which includes two core clades—Chlorophyta and Streptophyta.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Most green chloroplasts are green in color, though some aren't due to accessory pigments that override the green from chlorophylls, such as in the resting cells of *Haematococcus pluvialis*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Green chloroplasts differ from glaucophyte and red algal chloroplasts in that they have lost their phycobilisomes, and contain chlorophyll *b*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] They have also lost the peptidoglycan wall between their double membrane, leaving an intermembrane space.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Some plants have kept some genes required for the synthesis of peptidoglycan, but have repurposed them for use in chloroplast division instead.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplastida lineages also keep their starch *inside* their chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In plants and some algae, the chloroplast thylakoids are arranged in grana stacks.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Some green algal chloroplasts, as well as those of hornworts, contain a structure called a pyrenoid, that concentrate RuBisCO and CO2 in the chloroplast, functionally similar to the glaucophyte carboxysome.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The photosynthetic amoeboids in the genus *Paulinella—P. chromatophora, P. micropora,* and marine *P. longichromatophora—*have the only known independently evolved chloroplast, often called a **chromatophore**.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] While all other chloroplasts originate from a single ancient endosymbiotic event, *Paulinella* independently acquired an endosymbiotic cyanobacterium from the genus *Synechococcus* around 90 – 140 million years ago.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Each *Paulinella* cell contains one or two sausage-shaped chloroplasts; they were first described in 1894 by German biologist Robert Lauterborn.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The chromatophore is highly reduced compared to its free-living cyanobacterial relatives and has limited functions.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] For example, it has a genome of about 1 million base pairs, one third the size of *Synechococcus* genomes, and only encodes around 850 proteins.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] However, this is still much larger than other chloroplast genomes, which are typically around 150,000 base pairs.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chromatophores have also transferred much less of their DNA to the nucleus of their hosts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] About 0.3–0.8% of the nuclear DNA in *Paulinella* is from the chromatophore, compared with 11–14% from the chloroplast in plants.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Similar to other chloroplasts, *Paulinella* provides specific proteins to the chromatophore using a specific targeting sequence.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Because chromatophores are much younger compared to the canonical chloroplasts, *Paulinella chromatophora* is studied to understand how early chloroplasts evolved.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Green algae have been taken up by many groups in three or four separate events.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Primarily, secondary chloroplasts derived from green algae are in the euglenoids and chlorarachniophytes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The euglenophytes are a group of common flagellated protists that contain chloroplasts derived from a green alga.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Euglenophytes are the only group outside Diaphoretickes that have chloroplasts without performing kleptoplasty.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Euglenophyte chloroplasts have three membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] It is thought that the membrane of the primary endosymbiont host was lost (e.g. the green algal membrane), leaving the two cyanobacterial membranes and the secondary host's phagosomal membrane.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Euglenophyte chloroplasts have a pyrenoid and thylakoids stacked in groups of three.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The carbon fixed through photosynthesis is stored in the form of paramylon, which is contained in membrane-bound granules in the cytoplasm of the euglenophyte.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chlorarachniophytes are a rare group of organisms that also contain chloroplasts derived from green algae, though their story is more complicated than that of the euglenophytes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The ancestor of chlorarachniophytes is thought to have been a eukaryote with a *red* algal derived chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] It is then thought to have lost its first red algal chloroplast, and later engulfed a green alga, giving it its second, green algal derived chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chlorarachniophyte chloroplasts are bounded by four membranes, except near the cell membrane, where the chloroplast membranes fuse into a double membrane.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Their thylakoids are arranged in loose stacks of three.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chlorarachniophytes have a form of polysaccharide called chrysolaminarin, which they store in the cytoplasm, often collected around the chloroplast pyrenoid, which bulges into the cytoplasm.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chlorarachniophyte chloroplasts are notable because the green alga they are derived from has not been completely broken down—its nucleus still persists as a nucleomorph found between the second and third chloroplast membranes—the periplasmic space, which corresponds to the green alga's cytoplasm.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Dinoflagellates in the genus *Lepidodinium* have lost their original peridinin chloroplast and replaced it with a green algal derived chloroplast (more specifically, a prasinophyte).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] *Lepidodinium* is the only dinoflagellate that has a chloroplast that's not from the rhodoplast lineage.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The chloroplast is surrounded by two membranes and has no nucleomorph—all the nucleomorph genes have been transferred to the dinophyte nucleus.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The endosymbiotic event that led to this chloroplast was serial secondary endosymbiosis rather than tertiary endosymbiosis—the endosymbiont was a green alga containing a primary chloroplast (making a secondary chloroplast).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The ciliate *Pseudoblepharisma tenue* has two bacterial symbionts, one pink, one green.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In 2021, both symbionts were confirmed to be photosynthetic: Ca.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] *Thiodictyon intracellulare* (Chromatiaceae), a purple sulfur bacterium with a genome just half the size of their closest known relatives; and *Chlorella* sp.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] There is also a variant of *Pseudoblepharisma tenue* that only contains chloroplasts from green algae and no endosymbiotic purple bacteria.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Secondary chloroplasts derived from red algae appear to have only been taken up only once, which then diversified into a large group called chromists or chromalveolates.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Today they are found in the haptophytes, cryptomonads, heterokonts, dinoflagellates and apicomplexans (the CASH lineage).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Red algal secondary chloroplasts usually contain chlorophyll c and are surrounded by four membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] However, chromist monophyly has been rejected, and it is considered more likely that some chromists acquired their plastids by incorporating another chromist instead of inheriting them from a common ancestor.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Cryptophytes seem to have acquired plastids from red algae, which were then transmitted from them to both the Heterokontophytes and the Haptophytes, and then from these last to the Myzozoa.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Cryptophytes, or cryptomonads, are a group of algae that contain a red-algal derived chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Cryptophyte chloroplasts contain a nucleomorph that superficially resembles that of the chlorarachniophytes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Cryptophyte chloroplasts have four membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The outermost membrane is continuous with the rough endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] They synthesize ordinary starch, which is stored in granules found in the periplastid space—outside the original double membrane, in the place that corresponds to the ancestral red alga's cytoplasm.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Inside cryptophyte chloroplasts is a pyrenoid and thylakoids in stacks of two.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Cryptophyte chloroplasts do not have phycobilisomes, but they do have phycobilin pigments which they keep in the thylakoid space, rather than anchored on the outside of their thylakoid membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Cryptophytes may have played a key role in the spreading of red algal based chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Haptophytes are similar and closely related to cryptophytes or heterokontophytes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Their chloroplasts lack a nucleomorph, their thylakoids are in stacks of three, and they synthesize chrysolaminarin sugar, which are stored in granules completely outside of the chloroplast, in the cytoplasm of the haptophyte.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The stramenopiles, also known as heterokontophytes, are a very large and diverse group of eukaryotes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] It inlcludes Ochrophyta—which includes diatoms, brown algae (seaweeds), and golden algae (chrysophytes)— and Xanthophyceae (also called yellow-green algae).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Heterokont chloroplasts are very similar to haptophyte chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] They have a pyrenoid, triplet thylakoids, and, with some exceptions, four layer plastidic envelope with the outermost membrane connected to the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Like haptophytes, stramenopiles store sugar in chrysolaminarin granules in the cytoplasm.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Stramenopile chloroplasts contain chlorophyll *a* and, with a few exceptions, chlorophyll *c*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] They also have carotenoids which give them their many colors.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The alveolates are a major clade of unicellular eukaryotes of both autotrophic and heterotrophic members.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Many members contain a red-algal derived plastid.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] One notable characteristic of this diverse group is the frequent loss of photosynthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] However, a majority of these heterotrophs continue to process a non-photosynthetic plastid.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Apicomplexans are a group of alveolates.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Like the helicosproidia, they're parasitic, and have a nonphotosynthetic chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] They were once thought to be related to the helicosproidia, but it is now known that the helicosproida are green algae rather than part of the CASH lineage.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The apicomplexans include *Plasmodium*, the malaria parasite.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Many apicomplexans keep a vestigial red algal derived chloroplast called an apicoplast, which they inherited from their ancestors.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Apicoplasts have lost all photosynthetic function, and contain no photosynthetic pigments or true thylakoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] They are bounded by four membranes, but the membranes are not connected to the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Other apicomplexans like *Cryptosporidium* have lost the chloroplast completely.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Apicomplexans store their energy in amylopectin granules that are located in their cytoplasm, even though they are nonphotosynthetic.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The fact that apicomplexans still keep their nonphotosynthetic chloroplast around demonstrates how the chloroplast carries out important functions other than photosynthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Plant chloroplasts provide plant cells with many important things besides sugar, and apicoplasts are no different—they synthesize fatty acids, isopentenyl pyrophosphate, iron-sulfur clusters, and carry out part of the heme pathway.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The most important apicoplast function is isopentenyl pyrophosphate synthesis—in fact, apicomplexans die when something interferes with this apicoplast function, and when apicomplexans are grown in an isopentenyl pyrophosphate-rich medium, they dump the organelle.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The chromerids are a group of algae known from Australian corals which comprise some close photosynthetic relatives of the apicomplexans.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The first member, *Chromera velia*, was discovered and first isolated in 2001.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The discovery of *Chromera velia* with similar structure to the apicomplexans, provides an important link in the evolutionary history of the apicomplexans and dinophytes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Their plastids have four membranes, lack chlorophyll c and use the type II form of RuBisCO obtained from a horizontal transfer event.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The dinoflagellates are yet another very large and diverse group, around half of which are at least partially photosynthetic (i.e. mixotrophic).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Dinoflagellate chloroplasts have relatively complex history.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Most dinoflagellate chloroplasts are secondary red algal derived chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Many dinoflagellates have lost the chloroplast (becoming nonphotosynthetic), some of these have replaced it though *tertiary* endosymbiosis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Others replaced their original chloroplast with a green algal derived chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The peridinin chloroplast is thought to be the dinophytes' "original" chloroplast, which has been lost, reduced, replaced, or has company in several other dinophyte lineages.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The most common dinophyte chloroplast is the peridinin-type chloroplast, characterized by the carotenoid pigment peridinin in their chloroplasts, along with chlorophyll *a* and chlorophyll *c*2.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Peridinin is not found in any other group of chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The peridinin chloroplast is bounded by three membranes (occasionally two), having lost the red algal endosymbiont's original cell membrane.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The outermost membrane is not connected to the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] They contain a pyrenoid, and have triplet-stacked thylakoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Starch is found outside the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Peridinin chloroplasts also have DNA that is highly reduced and fragmented into many small circles.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Most of the genome has migrated to the nucleus, and only critical photosynthesis-related genes remain in the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Most dinophyte chloroplasts contain form II RuBisCO, at least the photosynthetic pigments chlorophyll *a*, chlorophyll *c2*, *beta*-carotene, and at least one dinophyte-unique xanthophyll (peridinin, dinoxanthin, or diadinoxanthin), giving many a golden-brown color.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] All dinophytes store starch in their cytoplasm, and most have chloroplasts with thylakoids arranged in stacks of three.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The fucoxanthin dinophyte lineages (including *Karlodinium* and *Karenia*) lost their original red algal derived chloroplast, and replaced it with a new chloroplast derived from a haptophyte endosymbiont, making these tertiary plastids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] *Karlodinium* and *Karenia* probably took up different endosymbionts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Because the haptophyte chloroplast has four membranes, tertiary endosymbiosis would be expected to create a six membraned chloroplast, adding the haptophyte's cell membrane and the dinophyte's phagosomal vacuole.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] However, the haptophyte was heavily reduced, stripped of a few membranes and its nucleus, leaving only its chloroplast (with its original double membrane), and possibly one or two additional membranes around it.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Fucoxanthin-containing chloroplasts are characterized by having the pigment fucoxanthin (actually 19′-hexanoyloxy-fucoxanthin and/or 19′-butanoyloxy-fucoxanthin) and no peridinin.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Fucoxanthin is also found in haptophyte chloroplasts, providing evidence of ancestry.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Some dinophytes, like *Kryptoperidinium* and *Durinskia*, have a diatom (heterokontophyte)-derived chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] These chloroplasts are bounded by up to *five* membranes, (depending on whether the entire diatom endosymbiont is counted as the chloroplast, or just the red algal derived chloroplast inside it).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The diatom endosymbiont has been reduced relatively little—it still retains its original mitochondria, and has endoplasmic reticulum, ribosomes, a nucleus, and of course, red algal derived chloroplasts—practically a complete cell, all inside the host's endoplasmic reticulum lumen.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] However the diatom endosymbiont can't store its own food—its storage polysaccharide is found in granules in the dinophyte host's cytoplasm instead.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The diatom endosymbiont's nucleus is present, but it probably can't be called a nucleomorph because it shows no sign of genome reduction, and might have even been *expanded*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Diatoms have been engulfed by dinoflagellates at least three times.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The diatom endosymbiont is bounded by a single membrane, inside it are chloroplasts with four membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Like the diatom endosymbiont's diatom ancestor, the chloroplasts have triplet thylakoids and pyrenoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In some of these genera, the diatom endosymbiont's chloroplasts aren't the only chloroplasts in the dinophyte.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The original three-membraned peridinin chloroplast is still around, converted to an eyespot.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In some groups of mixotrophic protists, like some dinoflagellates (e.g.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] *Dinophysis*), chloroplasts are separated from a captured alga and used temporarily.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] These klepto chloroplasts may only have a lifetime of a few days and are then replaced.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Members of the genus *Dinophysis* have a phycobilin-containing chloroplast taken from a cryptophyte.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] However, the cryptophyte is not an endosymbiont—only the chloroplast seems to have been taken, and the chloroplast has been stripped of its nucleomorph and outermost two membranes, leaving just a two-membraned chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplasts, like other endosymbiotic organelles, contain a genome separate from that in the cell nucleus.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The existence of chloroplast DNA (cpDNA) was identified biochemically in 1959, and confirmed by electron microscopy in 1962.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The discoveries that the chloroplast contains ribosomes and performs protein synthesis revealed that the chloroplast is genetically semi-autonomous.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplast DNA was first sequenced in 1986.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] , segments with labels on the outside are on the A strand.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] With few exceptions, most chloroplasts have their entire genome combined into a single large circular DNA molecule, typically 120,000–170,000 base pairs long and a mass of about 80–130 million daltons.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] While chloroplast genomes can almost always be assembled into a circular map, the physical DNA molecules inside cells take on a variety of linear and branching forms.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] New chloroplasts may contain up to 100 copies of their genome, though the number of copies decreases to about 15–20 as the chloroplasts age.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplast DNA is usually condensed into nucleoids, which can contain multiple copies of the chloroplast genome.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Many nucleoids can be found in each chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In primitive red algae, the chloroplast DNA nucleoids are clustered in the center of the chloroplast, while in green plants and green algae, the nucleoids are dispersed throughout the stroma.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplast DNA is not associated with true histones, proteins that are used to pack DNA molecules tightly in eukaryote nuclei.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Though in red algae, similar proteins tightly pack each chloroplast DNA ring in a nucleoid.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Many chloroplast genomes contain two inverted repeats, which separate a long single copy section (LSC) from a short single copy section (SSC).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] A given pair of inverted repeats are rarely identical, but they are always very similar to each other, apparently resulting from concerted evolution.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The inverted repeats vary wildly in length, ranging from 4,000 to 25,000 base pairs long each and containing as few as four or as many as over 150 genes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The inverted repeat regions are highly conserved in land plants, and accumulate few mutations.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Similar inverted repeats exist in the genomes of cyanobacteria and the other two chloroplast lineages (glaucophyta and rhodophyceae), suggesting that they predate the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Some chloroplast genomes have since lost or flipped the inverted repeats (making them direct repeats).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] It is possible that the inverted repeats help stabilize the rest of the chloroplast genome, as chloroplast genomes which have lost some of the inverted repeat segments tend to get rearranged more.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In chloroplasts of the moss *Physcomitrella patens*, the DNA mismatch repair protein Msh1 interacts with the recombinational repair proteins RecA and RecG to maintain chloroplast genome stability.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In chloroplasts of the plant *Arabidopsis thaliana* the RecA protein maintains the integrity of the chloroplast's DNA by a process that likely involves the recombinational repair of DNA damage.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The mechanism for chloroplast DNA (cpDNA) replication has not been conclusively determined, but two main models have been proposed.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Scientists have attempted to observe chloroplast replication via electron microscopy since the 1970s.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The results of the microscopy experiments led to the idea that chloroplast DNA replicates using a double displacement loop (D-loop).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] As the D-loop moves through the circular DNA, it adopts a theta intermediary form, also known as a Cairns replication intermediate, and completes replication with a rolling circle mechanism.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Transcription starts at specific points of origin.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Multiple replication forks open up, allowing replication machinery to transcribe the DNA.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] As replication continues, the forks grow and eventually converge.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The new cpDNA structures separate, creating daughter cpDNA chromosomes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In addition to the early microscopy experiments, this model is also supported by the amounts of deamination seen in cpDNA.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Deamination occurs when an amino group is lost and is a mutation that often results in base changes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] When adenine is deaminated, it becomes hypoxanthine.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Hypoxanthine can bind to cytosine, and when the XC base pair is replicated, it becomes a GC (thus, an A → G base change).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In cpDNA, there are several A → G deamination gradients.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] DNA becomes susceptible to deamination events when it is single stranded.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] When replication forks form, the strand not being copied is single stranded, and thus at risk for A → G deamination.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Therefore, gradients in deamination indicate that replication forks were most likely present and the direction that they initially opened (the highest gradient is most likely nearest the start site because it was single stranded for the longest amount of time).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] This mechanism is still the leading theory today; however, a second theory suggests that most cpDNA is actually linear and replicates through homologous recombination.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] It further contends that only a minority of the genetic material is kept in circular chromosomes while the rest is in branched, linear, or other complex structures.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] One of competing model for cpDNA replication asserts that most cpDNA is linear and participates in homologous recombination and replication structures similar to the linear and circular DNA structures of bacteriophage T4.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] It has been established that some plants have linear cpDNA, such as maize, and that more species still contain complex structures that scientists do not yet understand.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] When the original experiments on cpDNA were performed, scientists did notice linear structures; however, they attributed these linear forms to broken circles.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] If the branched and complex structures seen in cpDNA experiments are real and not artifacts of concatenated circular DNA or broken circles, then a D-loop mechanism of replication is insufficient to explain how those structures would replicate.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] At the same time, homologous recombination does not expand the multiple A --> G gradients seen in plastomes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Because of the failure to explain the deamination gradient as well as the numerous plant species that have been shown to have circular cpDNA, the predominant theory continues to hold that most cpDNA is circular and most likely replicates via a D loop mechanism.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The ancestral cyanobacteria that led to chloroplasts probably had a genome that contained over 3000 genes, but only approximately 100 genes remain in contemporary chloroplast genomes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] These genes code for a variety of things, mostly to do with the protein pipeline and photosynthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] As in prokaryotes, genes in chloroplast DNA are organized into operons.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Unlike prokaryotic DNA molecules, chloroplast DNA molecules contain introns (plant mitochondrial DNAs do too, but not human mtDNAs).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Among land plants, the contents of the chloroplast genome are fairly similar.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Over time, many parts of the chloroplast genome were transferred to the nuclear genome of the host, a process called *endosymbiotic gene transfer*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] As a result, the chloroplast genome is heavily reduced compared to that of free-living cyanobacteria.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplasts may contain 60–100 genes whereas cyanobacteria often have more than 1500 genes in their genome.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Recently, a plastid without a genome was found, demonstrating chloroplasts can lose their genome during endosymbiotic the gene transfer process.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Endosymbiotic gene transfer is how we know about the lost chloroplasts in many CASH lineages.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Even if a chloroplast is eventually lost, the genes it donated to the former host's nucleus persist, providing evidence for the lost chloroplast's existence.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In land plants, some 11–14% of the DNA in their nuclei can be traced back to the chloroplast, up to 18% in *Arabidopsis*, corresponding to about 4,500 protein-coding genes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] There have been a few recent transfers of genes from the chloroplast DNA to the nuclear genome in land plants.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Of the approximately 3000 proteins found in chloroplasts, some 95% of them are encoded by nuclear genes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Many of the chloroplast's protein complexes consist of subunits from both the chloroplast genome and the host's nuclear genome.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] As a result, protein synthesis must be coordinated between the chloroplast and the nucleus.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The chloroplast is mostly under nuclear control, though chloroplasts can also give out signals regulating gene expression in the nucleus, called *retrograde signaling*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Recent research indicates that parts of the retrograde signaling network once considered characteristic for land plants emerged already in an algal progenitor, integrating into co-expressed cohorts of genes in the closest algal relatives of land plants.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Protein synthesis within chloroplasts relies on two RNA polymerases.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] One is coded by the chloroplast DNA, the other is of nuclear origin.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The two RNA polymerases may recognize and bind to different kinds of promoters within the chloroplast genome.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] The ribosomes in chloroplasts are similar to bacterial ribosomes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Because so many chloroplast genes have been moved to the nucleus, many proteins that would originally have been translated in the chloroplast are now synthesized in the cytoplasm of the plant cell.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] These proteins must be directed back to the chloroplast, and imported through at least two chloroplast membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Curiously, around half of the protein products of transferred genes aren't even targeted back to the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Many became exaptations, taking on new functions like participating in cell division, protein routing, and even disease resistance.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] A few chloroplast genes found new homes in the mitochondrial genome—most became nonfunctional pseudogenes, though a few tRNA genes still work in the mitochondrion.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In those cases, chloroplast-targeted proteins do initially travel along the secretory pathway.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Because the cell acquiring a chloroplast already had mitochondria (and peroxisomes, and a cell membrane for secretion), the new chloroplast host had to develop a unique protein targeting system to avoid having chloroplast proteins being sent to the wrong organelle.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] In most, but not all cases, nuclear-encoded chloroplast proteins are translated with a *cleavable transit peptide* that's added to the N-terminus of the protein precursor.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Sometimes the transit sequence is found on the C-terminus of the protein, or within the functional part of the protein.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] After a chloroplast polypeptide is synthesized on a ribosome in the cytosol, an enzyme specific to chloroplast proteins phosphorylates, or adds a phosphate group to many (but not all) of them in their transit sequences.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Phosphorylation helps many proteins bind the polypeptide, keeping it from folding prematurely.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] This is important because it prevents chloroplast proteins from assuming their active form and carrying out their chloroplast functions in the wrong place—the cytosol.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] At the same time, they have to keep just enough shape so that they can be recognized by the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] These proteins also help the polypeptide get imported into the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] From here, chloroplast proteins bound for the stroma must pass through two protein complexes—the TOC complex, or ***t**ranslocon on the **o**uter **c**hloroplast membrane*, and the TIC translocon, or ***t**ranslocon on the **i**nner **c**hloroplast membrane translocon*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p01] Chloroplast polypeptide chains probably often travel through the two complexes at the same time, but the TIC complex can also retrieve preproteins lost in the intermembrane space.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In land plants, chloroplasts are generally lens-shaped, 3–10 μm in diameter and 1–3 μm thick.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Corn seedling chloroplasts are ≈20 μm3 in volume.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Some algae have two chloroplasts in each cell; they are star-shaped in *Zygnema*, or may follow the shape of half the cell in order Desmidiales.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In some algae, the chloroplast takes up most of the cell, with pockets for the nucleus and other organelles, for example, some species of *Chlorella* have a cup-shaped chloroplast that occupies much of the cell.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] All chloroplasts have at least three membrane systems—the outer chloroplast membrane, the inner chloroplast membrane, and the thylakoid system.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The two innermost lipid-bilayer membranes that surround all chloroplasts correspond to the outer and inner membranes of the ancestral cyanobacterium's gram negative cell wall, and not the phagosomal membrane from the host, which was probably lost.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplasts that are the product of secondary endosymbiosis may have additional membranes surrounding these three.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Inside the outer and inner chloroplast membranes is the chloroplast stroma, a semi-gel-like fluid that makes up much of a chloroplast's volume, and in which the thylakoid system floats.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] There are some common misconceptions about the outer and inner chloroplast membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The fact that chloroplasts are surrounded by a double membrane is often cited as evidence that they are the descendants of endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] This is often interpreted as meaning the outer chloroplast membrane is the product of the host's cell membrane infolding to form a vesicle to surround the ancestral cyanobacterium—which is not true—both chloroplast membranes are homologous to the cyanobacterium's original double membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The chloroplast double membrane is also often compared to the mitochondrial double membrane.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] This is not a valid comparison—the inner mitochondria membrane is used to run proton pumps and carry out oxidative phosphorylation across to generate ATP energy.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The only chloroplast structure that can be considered analogous to it is the internal thylakoid system.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Even so, in terms of "in-out", the direction of chloroplast H+ ion flow is in the opposite direction compared to oxidative phosphorylation in mitochondria.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In addition, in terms of function, the inner chloroplast membrane, which regulates metabolite passage and synthesizes some materials, has no counterpart in the mitochondrion.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The outer chloroplast membrane is a semi-porous membrane that small molecules and ions can easily diffuse across.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] However, it is not permeable to larger proteins, so chloroplast polypeptides being synthesized in the cell cytoplasm must be transported across the outer chloroplast membrane by the TOC complex, or ***t**ranslocon on the **o**uter **c**hloroplast* membrane.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The chloroplast membranes sometimes protrude out into the cytoplasm, forming a stromule, or **strom**a-containing tub**ule**.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Stromules are very rare in chloroplasts, and are much more common in other plastids like chromoplasts and amyloplasts in petals and roots, respectively.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They may exist to increase the chloroplast's surface area for cross-membrane transport, because they are often branched and tangled with the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] When they were first observed in 1962, some plant biologists dismissed the structures as artifactual, claiming that stromules were just oddly shaped chloroplasts with constricted regions or dividing chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] However, there is a growing body of evidence that stromules are functional, integral features of plant cell plastids, not merely artifacts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Usually, a thin intermembrane space about 10–20 nanometers thick exists between the outer and inner chloroplast membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Glaucophyte algal chloroplasts have a peptidoglycan layer between the chloroplast membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] It corresponds to the peptidoglycan cell wall of their cyanobacterial ancestors, which is located between their two cell membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] These chloroplasts are called *muroplasts* (from Latin *"mura"*, meaning "wall").
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Other chloroplasts were assumed to have lost the cyanobacterial wall, leaving an intermembrane space between the two chloroplast envelope membranes, but has since been found also in moss, lycophytes and ferns.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The inner chloroplast membrane borders the stroma and regulates passage of materials in and out of the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] After passing through the TOC complex in the outer chloroplast membrane, polypeptides must pass through the TIC complex *(**t**ranslocon on the **i**nner **c**hloroplast membrane)* which is located in the inner chloroplast membrane.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In addition to regulating the passage of materials, the inner chloroplast membrane is where fatty acids, lipids, and carotenoids are synthesized.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Some chloroplasts contain a structure called the chloroplast peripheral reticulum.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] It is often found in the chloroplasts of C4 plants, though it has also been found in some C3 angiosperms, and even some gymnosperms.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The chloroplast peripheral reticulum consists of a maze of membranous tubes and vesicles continuous with the inner chloroplast membrane that extends into the internal stromal fluid of the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Its purpose is thought to be to increase the chloroplast's surface area for cross-membrane transport between its stroma and the cell cytoplasm.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The small vesicles sometimes observed may serve as transport vesicles to shuttle stuff between the thylakoids and intermembrane space.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The protein-rich, alkaline, aqueous fluid within the inner chloroplast membrane and outside of the thylakoid space is called the stroma, which corresponds to the cytosol of the original cyanobacterium.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Nucleoids of chloroplast DNA, chloroplast ribosomes, the thylakoid system with plastoglobuli, starch granules, and many proteins can be found floating around in it.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The Calvin cycle, which fixes CO2 into G3P takes place in the stroma.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Comparison of a chloroplast ribosome (green) and a bacterial ribosome (yellow).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Important features common to both ribosomes and chloroplast-unique features are labeled.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplasts have their own ribosomes, which they use to synthesize a small fraction of their proteins.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplast ribosomes are about two-thirds the size of cytoplasmic ribosomes (around 17 nm vs 25 nm).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They take mRNAs transcribed from the chloroplast DNA and translate them into protein.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] While similar to bacterial ribosomes, chloroplast translation is more complex than in bacteria, so chloroplast ribosomes include some chloroplast-unique features.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Small subunit ribosomal RNAs in several Chlorophyta and euglenid chloroplasts lack motifs for Shine-Dalgarno sequence recognition, which is considered essential for translation initiation in most chloroplasts and prokaryotes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Such loss is also rarely observed in other plastids and prokaryotes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] An additional 4.5S rRNA with homology to the 3' tail of 23S is found in "higher" plants.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Plastoglobuli (**singular** *plastoglobulus*, sometimes spelled *plastoglobule(s)*), are spherical bubbles of lipids and proteins about 45–60 nanometers across.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They are surrounded by a lipid monolayer.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Plastoglobuli are found in all chloroplasts, but become more common when the chloroplast is under oxidative stress, or when it ages and transitions into a gerontoplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Plastoglobuli also exhibit a greater size variation under these conditions.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They are also common in etioplasts, but decrease in number as the etioplasts mature into chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Plastoglobuli contain both structural proteins and enzymes involved in lipid synthesis and metabolism.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They contain many types of lipids including plastoquinone, vitamin E, carotenoids and chlorophylls.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Plastoglobuli were once thought to be free-floating in the stroma, but it is now thought that they are permanently attached either to a thylakoid or to another plastoglobulus attached to a thylakoid, a configuration that allows a plastoglobulus to exchange its contents with the thylakoid network.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In normal green chloroplasts, the vast majority of plastoglobuli occur singularly, attached directly to their parent thylakoid.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In old or stressed chloroplasts, plastoglobuli tend to occur in linked groups or chains, still always anchored to a thylakoid.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Plastoglobuli form when a bubble appears between the layers of the lipid bilayer of the thylakoid membrane, or bud from existing plastoglobuli—though they never detach and float off into the stroma.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Practically all plastoglobuli form on or near the highly curved edges of the thylakoid disks or sheets.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They are also more common on stromal thylakoids than on granal ones.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] , a green alga that contains a pyrenoid surrounded by starch.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Starch granules are very common in chloroplasts, typically taking up 15% of the organelle's volume, though in some other plastids like amyloplasts, they can be big enough to distort the shape of the organelle.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Starch granules are simply accumulations of starch in the stroma, and are not bounded by a membrane.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Starch granules vary in composition and location across different chloroplast lineages.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In red algae, starch granules are found in the cytoplasm rather than in the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In C4 plants, mesophyll chloroplasts, which do not synthesize sugars, lack starch granules.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The chloroplast stroma contains many proteins, though the most common and important is RuBisCO, which is probably also the most abundant protein on the planet.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] RuBisCO is the enzyme that fixes CO2 into sugar molecules.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In C3 plants, RuBisCO is abundant in all chloroplasts, though in C4 plants, it is confined to the bundle sheath chloroplasts, where the Calvin cycle is carried out in C4 plants.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The chloroplasts of some hornworts and algae contain structures called pyrenoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Pyrenoids are roughly spherical and highly refractive bodies which are a site of starch accumulation in plants that contain them.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They consist of a matrix opaque to electrons, surrounded by two hemispherical starch plates.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The starch is accumulated as the pyrenoids mature.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In algae with carbon concentrating mechanisms, the enzyme RuBisCO is found in the pyrenoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Starch can also accumulate around the pyrenoids when CO2 is scarce.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Pyrenoids can divide to form new pyrenoids, or be produced "de novo".
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Thylakoids (sometimes spelled *thylakoïds*), are small interconnected sacks which contain the membranes that the light reactions of photosynthesis take place on.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The word *thylakoid* comes from the Greek word *thylakos* which means "sack".
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Suspended within the chloroplast stroma is the thylakoid system, a highly dynamic collection of membranous sacks called thylakoids where chlorophyll is found and the light reactions of photosynthesis happen.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In most vascular plant chloroplasts, the thylakoids are arranged in stacks called grana, though in certain C4 plant chloroplasts and some algal chloroplasts, the thylakoids are free floating.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Using a light microscope, it is just barely possible to see tiny green granules—which were named grana.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] With electron microscopy, it became possible to see the thylakoid system in more detail, revealing it to consist of stacks of flat thylakoids which made up the grana, and long interconnecting stromal thylakoids which linked different grana.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In the transmission electron microscope, thylakoid membranes appear as alternating light-and-dark bands, 8.5 nanometers thick.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The three-dimensional structure of the thylakoid membrane system has been disputed.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Many models have been proposed, the most prevalent being the helical model, in which granum stacks of thylakoids are wrapped by helical stromal thylakoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The helical model was supported by several additional works, but ultimately it was determined in 2019 that features from both the helical and bifurcation models are consolidated by newly discovered left-handed helical membrane junctions.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Likely for ease, the thylakoid system is still commonly depicted by older "hub and spoke" models where the grana are connected to each other by tubes of stromal thylakoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Grana consist of a stacks of flattened circular granal thylakoids that resemble pancakes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Each granum can contain anywhere from two to a hundred thylakoids, though grana with 10–20 thylakoids are most common.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Wrapped around the grana are multiple parallel right-handed helical stromal thylakoids, also known as frets or lamellar thylakoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The helices ascend at an angle of ~20°, connecting to each granal thylakoid at a bridge-like slit junction.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The stroma lamellae extend as large sheets perpendicular to the grana columns.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] These sheets are connected to the right-handed helices either directly or through bifurcations that form left-handed helical membrane surfaces.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The left-handed helical surfaces have a similar tilt angle to the right-handed helices (~20°), but ¼ the pitch.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Approximately 4 left-handed helical junctions are present per granum, resulting in a pitch-balanced array of right- and left-handed helical membrane surfaces of different radii and pitch that consolidate the network with minimal surface and bending energies.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] While different parts of the thylakoid system contain different membrane proteins, the thylakoid membranes are continuous and the thylakoid space they enclose form a single continuous labyrinth.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Embedded in the thylakoid membranes are important protein complexes which carry out the light reactions of photosynthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Photosystem II and photosystem I contain light-harvesting complexes with chlorophyll and carotenoids that absorb light energy and use it to energize electrons.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Molecules in the thylakoid membrane use the energized electrons to pump hydrogen ions into the thylakoid space, decreasing the pH and turning it acidic.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] ATP synthase is a large protein complex that harnesses the concentration gradient of the hydrogen ions in the thylakoid space to generate ATP energy as the hydrogen ions flow back out into the stroma—much like a dam turbine.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] There are two types of thylakoids—granal thylakoids, which are arranged in grana, and stromal thylakoids, which are in contact with the stroma.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Granal thylakoids are pancake-shaped circular disks about 300–600 nanometers in diameter.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Stromal thylakoids are helicoid sheets that spiral around grana.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The flat tops and bottoms of granal thylakoids contain only the relatively flat photosystem II protein complex.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] This allows them to stack tightly, forming grana with many layers of tightly appressed membrane, called granal membrane, increasing stability and surface area for light capture.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In contrast, photosystem I and ATP synthase are large protein complexes which jut out into the stroma.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They can't fit in the appressed granal membranes, and so are found in the stromal thylakoid membrane—the edges of the granal thylakoid disks and the stromal thylakoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] These large protein complexes may act as spacers between the sheets of stromal thylakoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The number of thylakoids and the total thylakoid area of a chloroplast is influenced by light exposure.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Shaded chloroplasts contain larger and more grana with more thylakoid membrane area than chloroplasts exposed to bright light, which have smaller and fewer grana and less thylakoid area.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Thylakoid extent can change within minutes of light exposure or removal.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Inside the photosystems embedded in chloroplast thylakoid membranes are various photosynthetic pigments, which absorb and transfer light energy.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The types of pigments found are different in various groups of chloroplasts, and are responsible for a wide variety of chloroplast colorations.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Other plastid types, such as the leucoplast and the chromoplast, contain little chlorophyll and do not carry out photosynthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] leaf extract shows the various pigments present in their chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chlorophyll *a* is found in all chloroplasts, as well as their cyanobacterial ancestors.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chlorophyll *a* is a blue-green pigment partially responsible for giving most cyanobacteria and chloroplasts their color.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Other forms of chlorophyll exist, such as the accessory pigments chlorophyll *b*, chlorophyll *c*, chlorophyll *d*, and chlorophyll *f*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chlorophyll *b* is an olive green pigment found only in the chloroplasts of plants, green algae, any secondary chloroplasts obtained through the secondary endosymbiosis of a green alga, and a few cyanobacteria.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] It is the chlorophylls *a* and *b* together that make most plant and green algal chloroplasts green.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chlorophyll *c* is mainly found in secondary endosymbiotic chloroplasts that originated from a red alga, although it is not found in chloroplasts of red algae themselves.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chlorophyll *c* is also found in some green algae and cyanobacteria.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chlorophylls *d* and *f* are pigments found only in some cyanobacteria.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In addition to chlorophylls, another group of yellow–orange pigments called carotenoids are also found in the photosystems.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] There are about thirty photosynthetic carotenoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They help transfer and dissipate excess energy, and their bright colors sometimes override the chlorophyll green, like during the fall, when the leaves of some land plants change color. β-carotene is a bright red-orange carotenoid found in nearly all chloroplasts, like chlorophyll *a*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Xanthophylls, especially the orange-red zeaxanthin, are also common.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Many other forms of carotenoids exist that are only found in certain groups of chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Phycobilins are a third group of pigments found in cyanobacteria, and glaucophyte, red algal, and cryptophyte chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Phycobilins come in all colors, though phycoerytherin is one of the pigments that makes many red algae red.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Phycobilins often organize into relatively large protein complexes about 40 nanometers across called phycobilisomes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Like photosystem I and ATP synthase, phycobilisomes jut into the stroma, preventing thylakoid stacking in red algal chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Cryptophyte chloroplasts and some cyanobacteria don't have their phycobilin pigments organized into phycobilisomes, and keep them in their thylakoid space instead.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Presence of pigments across chloroplast groups and cyanobacteria.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Colored cells represent pigment presence.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] To fix carbon dioxide into sugar molecules in the process of photosynthesis, chloroplasts use an enzyme called RuBisCO.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] RuBisCO has trouble distinguishing between carbon dioxide and oxygen, so at high oxygen concentrations, RuBisCO starts accidentally adding oxygen to sugar precursors.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] This has the result of ATP energy being wasted and CO2 being released, all with no sugar being produced.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] This is a big problem, since O2 is produced by the initial light reactions of photosynthesis, causing issues down the line in the Calvin cycle which uses RuBisCO.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] C4 plants evolved a way to solve this—by spatially separating the light reactions and the Calvin cycle.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The light reactions, which store light energy in ATP and NADPH, are done in the mesophyll cells of a C4 leaf.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The Calvin cycle, which uses the stored energy to make sugar using RuBisCO, is done in the bundle sheath cells, a layer of cells surrounding a vein in a leaf.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] As a result, chloroplasts in C4 mesophyll cells and bundle sheath cells are specialized for each stage of photosynthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In mesophyll cells, chloroplasts are specialized for the light reactions, so they lack RuBisCO, and have normal grana and thylakoids, which they use to make ATP and NADPH, as well as oxygen.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They store CO2 in a four-carbon compound, which is why the process is called *C4 photosynthesis*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The four-carbon compound is then transported to the bundle sheath chloroplasts, where it drops off CO2 and returns to the mesophyll.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Bundle sheath chloroplasts do not carry out the light reactions, preventing oxygen from building up in them and disrupting RuBisCO activity.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Because of this, they lack thylakoids organized into grana stacks—though bundle sheath chloroplasts still have free-floating thylakoids in the stroma where they still carry out cyclic electron flow, a light-driven method of synthesizing ATP to power the Calvin cycle without generating oxygen.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They lack photosystem II, and only have photosystem I—the only protein complex needed for cyclic electron flow.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Because the job of bundle sheath chloroplasts is to carry out the Calvin cycle and make sugar, they often contain large starch grains.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Both types of chloroplast contain large amounts of chloroplast peripheral reticulum, which they use to get more surface area to transport stuff in and out of them.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Mesophyll chloroplasts have a little more peripheral reticulum than bundle sheath chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Unlike most epidermal cells, the guard cells of plant stomata contain relatively well-developed chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] However, exactly what they do is controversial.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Plants lack specialized immune cells—all plant cells participate in the plant immune response.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplasts, along with the nucleus, cell membrane, and endoplasmic reticulum, are key players in pathogen defense.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Due to its role in a plant cell's immune response, pathogens frequently target the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Plants have two main immune responses—the hypersensitive response, in which infected cells seal themselves off and undergo programmed cell death, and systemic acquired resistance, where infected cells release signals warning the rest of the plant of a pathogen's presence.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplasts stimulate both responses by purposely damaging their photosynthetic system, producing reactive oxygen species.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] High levels of reactive oxygen species will cause the hypersensitive response.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The reactive oxygen species also directly kill any pathogens within the cell.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Lower levels of reactive oxygen species initiate systemic acquired resistance, triggering defense-molecule production in the rest of the plant.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In some plants, chloroplasts are known to move closer to the infection site and the nucleus during an infection.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplasts can serve as cellular sensors.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] After detecting stress in a cell, which might be due to a pathogen, chloroplasts begin producing molecules like salicylic acid, jasmonic acid, nitric oxide and reactive oxygen species which can serve as defense-signals.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] As cellular signals, reactive oxygen species are unstable molecules, so they probably don't leave the chloroplast, but instead pass on their signal to an unknown second messenger molecule.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] All these molecules initiate retrograde signaling—signals from the chloroplast that regulate gene expression in the nucleus.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In addition to defense signaling, chloroplasts, with the help of the peroxisomes, help synthesize an important defense molecule, jasmonate.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplasts synthesize all the fatty acids in a plant cell—linoleic acid, a fatty acid, is a precursor to jasmonate.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] One of the main functions of the chloroplast is its role in photosynthesis, the process by which light is transformed into chemical energy, to subsequently produce food in the form of sugars.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Water (H2O) and carbon dioxide (CO2) are used in photosynthesis, and sugar and oxygen (O2) are made, using light energy.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Photosynthesis is divided into two stages—the light reactions, where water is split to produce oxygen, and the dark reactions, or Calvin cycle, which builds sugar molecules from carbon dioxide.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The two phases are linked by the energy carriers adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADP+).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The light reactions take place on the thylakoid membranes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They take light energy and store it in NADPH, a form of NADP+, and ATP to fuel the dark reactions.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] ATP is the phosphorylated version of adenosine diphosphate (ADP), which stores energy in a cell and powers most cellular activities.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] ATP is the energized form, while ADP is the (partially) depleted form.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] NADP+ is an electron carrier which ferries high energy electrons.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In the light reactions, it gets reduced, meaning it picks up electrons, becoming NADPH.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Like mitochondria, chloroplasts use the potential energy stored in an H+, or hydrogen ion, gradient to generate ATP energy.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The two photosystems capture light energy to energize electrons taken from water, and release them down an electron transport chain.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The molecules between the photosystems harness the electrons' energy to pump hydrogen ions into the thylakoid space, creating a concentration gradient, with more hydrogen ions (up to a thousand times as many) inside the thylakoid system than in the stroma.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The hydrogen ions in the thylakoid space then diffuse back down their concentration gradient, flowing back out into the stroma through ATP synthase.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] ATP synthase uses the energy from the flowing hydrogen ions to phosphorylate adenosine diphosphate into adenosine triphosphate, or ATP.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Because chloroplast ATP synthase projects out into the stroma, the ATP is synthesized there, in position to be used in the dark reactions.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Electrons are often removed from the electron transport chains to charge NADP+ with electrons, reducing it to NADPH.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Like ATP synthase, ferredoxin-NADP+ reductase, the enzyme that reduces NADP+, releases the NADPH it makes into the stroma, right where it is needed for the dark reactions.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Because NADP+ reduction removes electrons from the electron transport chains, they must be replaced—the job of photosystem II, which splits water molecules (H2O) to obtain the electrons from its hydrogen atoms.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] While photosystem II photolyzes water to obtain and energize new electrons, photosystem I simply reenergizes depleted electrons at the end of an electron transport chain.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Normally, the reenergized electrons are taken by NADP+, though sometimes they can flow back down more H+-pumping electron transport chains to transport more hydrogen ions into the thylakoid space to generate more ATP.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] This is termed cyclic photophosphorylation because the electrons are recycled.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Cyclic photophosphorylation is common in C4 plants, which need more ATP than NADPH.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] incorporates carbon dioxide into sugar molecules.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The Calvin cycle, also known as the dark reactions, is a series of biochemical reactions that fixes CO2 into G3P sugar molecules and uses the energy and electrons from the ATP and NADPH made in the light reactions.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The Calvin cycle takes place in the stroma of the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] While named *"the dark reactions"*, in most plants, they take place in the light, since the dark reactions are dependent on the products of the light reactions.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The Calvin cycle starts by using the enzyme RuBisCO to fix CO2 into five-carbon Ribulose bisphosphate (RuBP) molecules.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The result is unstable six-carbon molecules that immediately break down into three-carbon molecules called 3-phosphoglyceric acid, or 3-PGA.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The ATP and NADPH made in the light reactions is used to convert the 3-PGA into glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate, or G3P sugar molecules.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Most of the G3P molecules are recycled back into RuBP using energy from more ATP, but one out of every six produced leaves the cycle—the end product of the dark reactions.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate can double up to form larger sugar molecules like glucose and fructose.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] These molecules are processed, and from them, the still larger sucrose, a disaccharide commonly known as table sugar, is made, though this process takes place outside of the chloroplast, in the cytoplasm.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Alternatively, glucose monomers in the chloroplast can be linked together to make starch, which accumulates into the starch grains found in the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Under conditions such as high atmospheric CO2 concentrations, these starch grains may grow very large, distorting the grana and thylakoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The starch granules displace the thylakoids, but leave them intact.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Waterlogged roots can also cause starch buildup in the chloroplasts, possibly due to less sucrose being exported out of the chloroplast (or more accurately, the plant cell).
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] This depletes a plant's free phosphate supply, which indirectly stimulates chloroplast starch synthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] While linked to low photosynthesis rates, the starch grains themselves may not necessarily interfere significantly with the efficiency of photosynthesis, and might simply be a side effect of another photosynthesis-depressing factor.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Photorespiration can occur when the oxygen concentration is too high.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] RuBisCO cannot distinguish between oxygen and carbon dioxide very well, so it can accidentally add O2 instead of CO2 to RuBP.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] This process reduces the efficiency of photosynthesis—it consumes ATP and oxygen, releases CO2, and produces no sugar.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] It can waste up to half the carbon fixed by the Calvin cycle.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Several mechanisms have evolved in different lineages that raise the carbon dioxide concentration relative to oxygen within the chloroplast, increasing the efficiency of photosynthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] These mechanisms are called carbon dioxide concentrating mechanisms, or CCMs.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] These include Crassulacean acid metabolism, C4 carbon fixation, and pyrenoids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplasts in C4 plants are notable as they exhibit a distinct chloroplast dimorphism.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Because of the H+ gradient across the thylakoid membrane, the interior of the thylakoid is acidic, with a pH around 4, while the stroma is slightly basic, with a pH of around 8.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The optimal stroma pH for the Calvin cycle is 8.1, with the reaction nearly stopping when the pH falls below 7.3.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] CO2 in water can form carbonic acid, which can disturb the pH of isolated chloroplasts, interfering with photosynthesis, even though CO2 is used in photosynthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] However, chloroplasts in living plant cells are not affected by this as much.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplasts can pump K+ and H+ ions in and out of themselves using a poorly understood light-driven transport system.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In the presence of light, the pH of the thylakoid lumen can drop up to 1.5 pH units, while the pH of the stroma can rise by nearly one pH unit.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplasts alone make almost all of a plant cell's amino acids in their stroma except the sulfur-containing ones like cysteine and methionine.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Cysteine is made in the chloroplast (the proplastid too) but it is also synthesized in the cytosol and mitochondria, probably because it has trouble crossing membranes to get to where it is needed.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The chloroplast is known to make the precursors to methionine but it is unclear whether the organelle carries out the last leg of the pathway or if it happens in the cytosol.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplasts make all of a cell's purines and pyrimidines—the nitrogenous bases found in DNA and RNA.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They also convert nitrite (NO2−) into ammonia (NH3) which supplies the plant with nitrogen to make its amino acids and nucleotides.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The plastid is the site of diverse and complex lipid synthesis in plants.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The carbon used to form the majority of the lipid is from acetyl-CoA, which is the decarboxylation product of pyruvate.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Pyruvate may enter the plastid from the cytosol by passive diffusion through the membrane after production in glycolysis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Pyruvate is also made in the plastid from phosphoenolpyruvate, a metabolite made in the cytosol from pyruvate or PGA.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Acetate in the cytosol is unavailable for lipid biosynthesis in the plastid.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The typical length of fatty acids produced in the plastid are 16 or 18 carbons, with 0-3 cis double bonds.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The biosynthesis of fatty acids from acetyl-CoA primarily requires two enzymes.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Acetyl-CoA carboxylase creates malonyl-CoA, used in both the first step and the extension steps of synthesis.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Fatty acid synthase (FAS) is a large complex of enzymes and cofactors including acyl carrier protein (ACP) which holds the acyl chain as it is synthesized.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The initiation of synthesis begins with the condensation of malonyl-ACP with acetyl-CoA to produce ketobutyryl-ACP.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] 2 reductions involving the use of NADPH and one dehydration creates butyryl-ACP.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Extension of the fatty acid comes from repeated cycles of malonyl-ACP condensation, reduction, and dehydration.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Other lipids are derived from the methyl-erythritol phosphate (MEP) pathway and consist of gibberelins, sterols, abscisic acid, phytol, and innumerable secondary metabolites.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Stomal guard cells also have chloroplasts, though much fewer than mesophyll cells.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Not all cells in a multicellular plant contain chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] All green parts of a plant contain chloroplasts as the color comes from the chlorophyll.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The plant cells which contain chloroplasts are usually parenchyma cells, though chloroplasts can also be found in collenchyma tissue.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] A plant cell which contains chloroplasts is known as a chlorenchyma cell.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] A typical chlorenchyma cell of a land plant contains about 10 to 100 chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In some plants such as cacti, chloroplasts are found in the stems, though in most plants, chloroplasts are concentrated in the leaves.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] One square millimeter of leaf tissue can contain half a million chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Within a leaf, chloroplasts are mainly found in the mesophyll layers of a leaf, and the guard cells of stomata.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Palisade mesophyll cells can contain 30–70 chloroplasts per cell, while stomatal guard cells contain only around 8–15 per cell, as well as much less chlorophyll.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplasts can also be found in the bundle sheath cells of a leaf, especially in C4 plants, which carry out the Calvin cycle in their bundle sheath cells.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They are often absent from the epidermis of a leaf.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] The chloroplasts of plant and algal cells can orient themselves to best suit the available light.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In low-light conditions, they will spread out in a sheet—maximizing the surface area to absorb light.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Under intense light, they will seek shelter by aligning in vertical columns along the plant cell's cell wall or turning sideways so that light strikes them edge-on.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] This reduces exposure and protects them from photooxidative damage.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] This ability to distribute chloroplasts so that they can take shelter behind each other or spread out may be the reason why land plants evolved to have many small chloroplasts instead of a few big ones.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Chloroplast movement is considered one of the most closely regulated stimulus-response systems that can be found in plants.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Mitochondria have also been observed to follow chloroplasts as they move.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In higher plants, chloroplast movement is run by phototropins, blue light photoreceptors also responsible for plant phototropism.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] In some algae, mosses, ferns, and flowering plants, chloroplast movement is influenced by red light in addition to blue light, though very long red wavelengths inhibit movement rather than speeding it up.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Blue light generally causes chloroplasts to seek shelter, while red light draws them out to maximize light absorption.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] Studies of *Vallisneria gigantea*, an aquatic flowering plant, have shown that chloroplasts can get moving within five minutes of light exposure, though they don't initially show any net directionality.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p02] They may move along microfilament tracks, and the fact that the microfilament mesh changes shape to form a honeycomb structure surrounding the chloroplasts after they have moved suggests that microfilaments may help to anchor chloroplasts in place.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Plants contain many different kinds of plastids in their cells.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Chloroplasts are a special type of a plant cell organelle called a **plastid**, though the two terms are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] There are many other types of plastids, which carry out various functions.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] All chloroplasts in a plant are descended from undifferentiated proplastids found in the zygote, or fertilized egg.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Proplastids are commonly found in an adult plant's apical meristems.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Chloroplasts do not normally develop from proplastids in root tip meristems—instead, the formation of starch-storing amyloplasts is more common.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] In shoots, proplastids from shoot apical meristems can gradually develop into chloroplasts in photosynthetic leaf tissues as the leaf matures, if exposed to the required light.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] This process involves invaginations of the inner plastid membrane, forming sheets of membrane that project into the internal stroma.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] These membrane sheets then fold to form thylakoids and grana.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] If angiosperm shoots are not exposed to the required light for chloroplast formation, proplastids may develop into an etioplast stage before becoming chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] An etioplast is a plastid that lacks chlorophyll, and has inner membrane invaginations that form a lattice of tubes in their stroma, called a prolamellar body.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] While etioplasts lack chlorophyll, they have a yellow chlorophyll precursor stocked.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Within a few minutes of light exposure, the prolamellar body begins to reorganize into stacks of thylakoids, and chlorophyll starts to be produced.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] This process, where the etioplast becomes a chloroplast, takes several hours.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Gymnosperms do not require light to form chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Light, however, does not guarantee that a proplastid will develop into a chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Whether a proplastid develops into a chloroplast some other kind of plastid is mostly controlled by the nucleus and is largely influenced by the kind of cell it resides in.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Many plastid interconversions are possible.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Plastid differentiation is not permanent, in fact many interconversions are possible.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Chloroplasts may be converted to chromoplasts, which are pigment-filled plastids responsible for the bright colors seen in flowers and ripe fruit.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Starch storing amyloplasts can also be converted to chromoplasts, and it is possible for proplastids to develop straight into chromoplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Chromoplasts and amyloplasts can also become chloroplasts, like what happens when a carrot or a potato is illuminated.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] If a plant is injured, or something else causes a plant cell to revert to a meristematic state, chloroplasts and other plastids can turn back into proplastids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Chloroplast, amyloplast, chromoplast, proplastid are not absolute; state—intermediate forms are common.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Most chloroplasts in a photosynthetic cell do not develop directly from proplastids or etioplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] In fact, a typical shoot meristematic plant cell contains only 7–20 proplastids.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] These proplastids differentiate into chloroplasts, which divide to create the 30–70 chloroplasts found in a mature photosynthetic plant cell.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] If the cell divides, chloroplast division provides the additional chloroplasts to partition between the two daughter cells.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] In single-celled algae, chloroplast division is the only way new chloroplasts are formed.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] There is no proplastid differentiation—when an algal cell divides, its chloroplast divides along with it, and each daughter cell receives a mature chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Almost all chloroplasts in a cell divide, rather than a small group of rapidly dividing chloroplasts.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Chloroplasts have no definite S-phase—their DNA replication is not synchronized or limited to that of their host cells.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Much of what we know about chloroplast division comes from studying organisms like *Arabidopsis* and the red alga *Cyanidioschyzon merolæ*.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] The division process starts when the proteins FtsZ1 and FtsZ2 assemble into filaments, and with the help of a protein ARC6, form a structure called a Z-ring within the chloroplast's stroma.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] The Min system manages the placement of the Z-ring, ensuring that the chloroplast is cleaved more or less evenly.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] The protein MinD prevents FtsZ from linking up and forming filaments.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Another protein ARC3 may also be involved, but it is not very well understood.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] These proteins are active at the poles of the chloroplast, preventing Z-ring formation there, but near the center of the chloroplast, MinE inhibits them, allowing the Z-ring to form.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Next, the two plastid-dividing rings, or PD rings form.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] The inner plastid-dividing ring is located in the inner side of the chloroplast's inner membrane, and is formed first.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] The outer plastid-dividing ring is found wrapped around the outer chloroplast membrane.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] It consists of filaments about 5 nanometers across, arranged in rows 6.4 nanometers apart, and shrinks to squeeze the chloroplast.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] This is when chloroplast constriction begins.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] In a few species like *Cyanidioschyzon merolæ*, chloroplasts have a third plastid-dividing ring located in the chloroplast's intermembrane space.
[src:chloroplast/chloroplast-p03] Late into the constriction phase, dynamin proteins assemble around the outer plastid-dividing ring, helping provide force to squeeze the chloroplast.
